Dataset.03: ISOLET¶

Additional Information

  • This data set was generated as follows. 150 subjects spoke the name of each letter of the alphabet twice. Hence, we have 52 training examples from each speaker. The speakers are grouped into sets of 30 speakers each, and are referred to as isolet1, isolet2, isolet3, isolet4, and isolet5. The data appears in isolet1+2+3+4.data in sequential order, first the speakers from isolet1, then isolet2, and so on. The test set, isolet5, is a separate file.
  • You will note that 3 examples are missing. I believe they were dropped due to difficulties in recording.
  • I believe this is a good domain for a noisy, perceptual task. It is also a very good domain for testing the scaling abilities of algorithms. For example, C4.5 on this domain is slower than backpropagation!
  • I have formatted the data for C4.5 and provided a C4.5-style names file as well.

import pandas as pd

# data (as pandas dataframes) 
train = pd.read_csv('isolet1+2+3+4.data', header = None) 
test = pd.read_csv('isolet5.data', header = None)

The dataset is already separated as train and test. However, features and target are to be decoupled. As column 617 is the target column, next step is to get sets sorted accordingly.

I will select 5 as it has relatively better avg. ROC among 5 different runs. Stochastic nature of the classifier may result in selecting different "better" min_samples_leaf values. I didn't want to select a lower or higher value as it might cause under/overfitting.

    for max_features in max_features_n:
        rf = RandomForestClassifier(max_features = 20*max_features)
        rf.fit(X_train, y_train_bnr)
        y_pred_rf = rf.predict(X_test)
        fpr = dict()

fig, axs = plt.subplots(10, 10, figsize=(50, 50))
for i in range(10):    
    for j in range(10):
        model = XGBClassifier(n_estimators = 20+10*i, max_depth = 4+j)
        evalset = [(X_train, y_train_bnr), (X_test,y_test_bnr)]
        model.fit(X_train, y_train_bnr, eval_set=evalset, verbose=False)
        model.set_params(eval_metric = 'logloss')
        y_pred_xgb = model.predict(X_test)
        score = accuracy_score(y_test_bnr, y_pred_xgb)
        results = model.evals_result()

        axs[i, j].plot(results['validation_0']['logloss'], label='train')
        axs[i, j].plot(results['validation_1']['logloss'], label='test')
        axs[i, j].set_title(str(20+10*i) + ', ' + str(4+j))

It is not easy to detect at sight. n_estimators should not be increased as curve flats out. I will get the values only and then decide which values I will use.

Cross-validation¶

In [160]:
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from numpy import mean
from numpy import absolute
from numpy import sqrt
cv = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=1, shuffle=True)
for clf in [knn, dt, rf, xgb]:
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, X, y if clf == knn else y_bnr, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)
    print(clf, ' : ', mean(absolute(scores)))

Accuracy scores and KFold CV scores led me to choose XGB.

  • its accuracy score is higher
  • its CV score is the lowest
  • RF's performance is slower
